    "http://schema.org/description": [
      {
        "@language": "fr",
        "@value": "Alvin Lucier was born in 1931 in Nashua (New Hampshire, USA). He was educated in Nashua public and parochial schools, the Portsmouth Abbey School, Yale, and Brandeis and spent two years in Rome on a Fulbright Scholarship. From 1962 to 1970 he taught at Brandeis, where he conducted the Brandeis University Chamber Chorus which devoted much of its time to the performance of new music. Since 1970 he has taught at Wesleyan University where he is John Spencer Camp Professor of Music. Lucier has pioneered in many areas of music composition and performance, including the notation of performers’..."
      }
    ],
    "@type": [
      "http://schema.org/Person"
    ]
  },
  {
